The Macedonians decided in a referendum whether they will change the name of their country
Macedonians decided in a referendum on Sunday whether their name would change to "Northern Macedonia," a gesture that would resolve a decades-long conflict with Greece, which had blocked its bid to join the European Union and NATO.
Greece, which has a province called Macedonia, maintains that the name of its northern neighbor is a claim of its territory and has banned its entry into NATO and the EU.
In June, both governments reached an agreement on the proposed new name, but nationalist opponents argue that the change would undermine the ethnic identity of the Slavic population, the majority in Macedonia.
President Gjorge Ivanov has said he will not vote in the referendum and a boycott campaign has cast doubt on whether the vote will reach the minimum 50% required for the referendum to be considered valid.
In the referendum ballot, the following question was asked: "Are you in favour of NATO and EU membership with the acceptance of the agreement with Greece?"
Supporters of the name change, including Prime Minister Zoran Zaev, argue that it is a price worth paying for Macedonia, one of the countries emerging from the disintegration of Yugoslavia, to try to access bodies such as the EU and NATO.
“Today I came to vote for the future of the country, for the young people of Macedonia, so that they can live freely under the protection of the European Union, because this means a safer life for all,” said Olivera Georgijevska, 79, in Skopje.
Although it will not be legally binding, many Members of Parliament have said that they will respect the outcome of the vote in order to make it decisive.
The change of name requires a two-thirds majority in Parliament.
The State Electoral Commission stated that, at one o’clock in the afternoon, no irregularities had been reported.
However, the turnout was only 16%, compared to 34% of the last parliamentary elections held in 2016, when 66% of registered voters cast their votes.
“I’ve come to vote for my children, our place is in Europe,” said Gjose Tanevski, 62, who was voting in the capital Skopje.
Macedonian Prime Minister Zoran Zaev, his wife Zorica and son Dushko cast their vote in Macedonia’s referendum on a name change for the country that would open the way to join NATO and the European Union in Strumica (Macedonia) on September 30, 2018.
In front of parliament in Skopje, Vladimir Kavardarkov, 54, prepared a small stage and removed chairs in front of tents planted by those who were going to boycott the referendum.
“We are in favor of entering NATO and the EU, but we want to do it with our heads held high, not through the back door,” Kavadarkov said.
“We are a poor country, but we have dignity.
If they do not want us to enter like Macedonia, we can establish relations with other countries, such as China and Russia, and be part of Eurasia integration.”
Prime Minister Zaev says NATO membership would provide the much-needed investment Macedonia, whose unemployment rate is over 20 percent.
"I think the vast majority will be in favor, as more than 80% of citizens are in favour of the EU and NATO," Zaev said after filing his vote.
He said a positive outcome would be a “confirmation of our future.”
A poll published Monday by the Policy Research Institute said that between 30 and 43% of voters would participate in the referendum, which is less than the required turnout.
Another survey conducted by Telma TV, from Macedonia, revealed that 57% of respondents planned to vote on Sunday.
Of these, 70% said they would vote in favour.
In order for the referendum to be considered a success, participation must be 50% plus one vote.
