'The sea belongs to us': landlocked Bolivia hopes court will reopen Pacific route
Sailors guard a naval headquarters in La Paz.
In public buildings there are navy blue flags.
From Lake Titicaca to the Amazon, the naval bases show the motto: "The sea belongs to us by right,
Recovering it is a duty.”
Throughout Bolivia, a land without sea, they still vividly remember the coast lost to Chile in a bloody conflict over resources that took place in the 19th century, in addition to the longing to sail again in the Pacific Ocean.
These hopes may be the highest in decades, as Bolivia awaits an International Court of Justice ruling on October 1, after five years of deliberations.
“Bolivia has the momentum, a spirit of unity and serenity, and of course it is waiting for the result with a positive vision,” said Roberto Calzadilla, a Bolivian diplomat.
Many Bolivians will observe the ruling of the International Court of Justice on big screens across the country, hoping that the court in The Hague will rule in favor of Bolivia’s claim that, after decades of intermittent talks, Chile has an obligation to negotiate to grant Bolivia a sovereign exit into the sea.
Evo Morales, the charismatic indigenous president of Bolivia, who is waging a controversial battle for re-election next year, also has a lot to say about Monday’s resolution.
“We are very close to returning to the Pacific Ocean,” he promised in late August.
However, some analysts believe that the court is unlikely to decide in favor of Bolivia and that the situation would change little if it did.
The UN body based in the Netherlands has no power to award Chilean territory and has stipulated that it will not determine the outcome of possible talks.
The fact that the International Court of Justice’s ruling comes just six months after the final allegations indicates that the case “was not complicated,” said Paz Zárate, a Chilean expert on international law.
Far from promoting the cause of Bolivia, the past four years may have hindered it.
“The problem of access to the sea has been hijacked by the current Bolivian administration,” Zárate said.
In addition, he suggested that Morales’ belligerent rhetoric has undermined any residual Chilean goodwill.
Bolivia and Chile will continue to talk at some point, but it will be extremely difficult to hold talks after this.
The two countries have not exchanged ambassadors since 1962.
Former President Eduardo Rodríguez Veltzé, Bolivia’s representative in The Hague, rejected the idea that the court’s decision-making was unusually fast.
On Monday, Bolivia will be offered “an extraordinary opportunity to open a new era of relations with Chile” and the possibility of “ending 139 years of disagreements with mutual benefits,” he said.
Likewise, Calzadilla denied that Morales, who is still one of the most popular presidents of Latin America, used the maritime theme as a political crutch.
"Bolivia will never give up its right to access the Pacific Ocean," he said.
“Resolution is an opportunity to see that we have to leave the past behind.”
