John Edward: Language skills are critical to the citizens of the world
Independent schools in Scotland have a track record of academic excellence that has continued in 2018 with another set of extraordinary exam results that is reinforced by the individual and collective successes harvested in the fields of sport, art, music and other community projects.
With more than 30,000 students across Scotland, these centres, represented by the Scottish Council of Independent Schools (SCIS), strive to deliver the highest level of service to students and parents.
Independent schools aim to prepare their students to continue their higher education studies, for the career they choose and for the place they occupy as citizens of the world.
As an educational sector that can design and implement an adapted curriculum, it is observed that modern languages remain a popular and desired subject in the centers.
As Nelson Mandela said, “If you speak to a man in a language he understands, the message comes to his head.
If you speak to him in his language, it reaches his heart.”
This is a powerful reminder that if you want to build relationships and build trust with people from other countries, you cannot rely solely on English.
If we take into account the recent results of this year’s exams, we can see that languages are at the top of the qualifiers, with the highest pass rates in independent schools.
In total, 68% of students who studied foreign languages obtained an A, the highest score.
The data, collected from the 74 centres that are part of the SCIS, showed that 72% of students obtained an A in Mandarin, while 72% of those who studied German, 69% of those who studied French and 63% of those who studied Spanish also obtained an A.
This shows that Scotland’s independent schools support foreign languages as a fundamental competence that children and young people will undoubtedly need in the future.
Currently, it is considered that, as a subject, languages are on the same level as CTIM (science, technology, engineering and mathematics) subjects in the curricula of independent schools and everywhere.
A 2014 survey by the UK Employment and Skills Commission found that, of the reasons given by employers for the difficulties they encountered in filling jobs, 17 % were attributed to a shortage of language skills.
Therefore, language skills are increasingly indispensable to prepare young people for their future careers.
Potential job opportunities that require languages are on the rise, so these skills are essential in a globalized world.
Regardless of which career you choose, if you have learned a second language, you will have a real advantage in the future thanks to a competition like this, which will last a lifetime.
Being able to communicate directly with people from foreign countries will allow that person to automatically advance the competition.
According to a YouGov survey of more than 4,000 adults in the UK in 2013, 75% of them did not speak any foreign language well enough to hold a conversation. It was also established that the only language spoken by a double-digit percentage, 15%, was French.
For this reason, investing in language teaching is now important for children today.
If they know several languages, especially those in developing economies, children will be equipped to have better opportunities to find quality employment.
In Scotland, each school will teach different languages.
Some centers will focus on the more classic modern languages, while others will teach the languages considered most important to the UK by 2020, such as Mandarin or Japanese.
Whatever the interests of a child, in independent schools you can always choose from several languages taught by teaching staff specialized in this subject.
Independent schools in Scotland dedicate all their efforts to providing a learning environment that prepares children and equips them with the skills they need to succeed, whatever the future holds.
At the moment, it is undeniable that, in a global business environment, languages continue to be of vital importance for the future of the country, so this must be reflected in education.
Indeed, modern languages must be considered "competencies for international communication".
Independent schools will continue to offer these options, diversity and excellence to young people in Scotland.
It has to be done.
John Edward is the Director of the Scottish Council of Independent Schools.
