North Korea says ‘there is no chance’ they will be disarmed unilaterally first if they don’t have confidence
On Saturday, the North Korean foreign minister informed the United Nations that the continuation of the sanctions deepened his distrust in the United States and that there was no chance that his country would unilaterally give up nuclear weapons under those circumstances.
Ri Yong Ho told the annual General Assembly that North Korea had taken “significant goodwill measures” over the past year, such as stopping nuclear and missile tests, dismantling facilities for nuclear tests and committing to the non-proliferation of nuclear weapons and nuclear technology.
"However, we did not receive any similar response from the United States," he said.
“If we don’t have confidence in the United States, we can’t have confidence in our national security, and in those circumstances, there is no chance that we will disarm unilaterally first.”
Although Ri repeated North Korea’s well-known complaints about Washington’s resistance to a “phased” denuclearization formula that rewards the country as it takes gradual steps, his statement is important as he did not immediately reject unilateral denuclearization, as Pyongyang has done in the past.
Ri referred to a joint statement issued by Kim Jong Un and Donald Trump following the first summit between an active U.S. president and a North Korean leader on June 12 in Singapore, when Kim pledged to work toward “denuclearization of the Korean Peninsula” and Trump secured North Korea’s security.
North Korea has pursued the official end of the 1950-53 Korean War, but the United States has said that Pyongyang must give up its nuclear weapons first.
Washington has also resisted calls to ease international sanctions on North Korea.
“The United States has insisted on denuclearization in the first place and has increased pressure through sanctions in order to achieve its purpose in a coercive manner, including by objecting to a declaration of war termination,” Ri said.
“The idea that sanctions can make us fall on our knees is a chimera of people who don’t know us.
The problem is that the continuation of sanctions deepens our distrust.”
Ri made no mention of plans for a second summit between Kim and Trump, announced in full swing by the U.S. leader at the United Nations earlier this week.
Instead, the minister highlighted three meetings between Kim and South Korea’s leader Moon Jae over the past five months, adding: “If South Korea had been the stakeholder in denuclearization instead of the United States, denuclearization of the Korean peninsula would not be in a similar stagnation.”
Even so, the tone of Ri’s speech was radically different from last year’s speech when he told the U.N. General Assembly that it was inevitable to direct North Korea’s missiles to U.S. soil after “evil president” Trump, on a suicide mission, called Kim a “rocket man.”
This year at the United Nations, Trump, who last year threatened to “totally destroy” North Korea, praised Kim for his bravery in advancing disarmament, but said much remained to be done and sanctions needed to continue until North Korea denuclearized.
On Wednesday, Trump said there was no set deadline for this: “We can take two years, three years or five months, it doesn’t matter.”
China and Russia argue that the UN Security Council should reward Pyongyang for its progress.
However, as US Secretary of State Mike Pompeo reported to the UN Security Council on Thursday: “The imposition of Security Council sanctions must continue vigorously and without non-compliance until we realize the definitive and fully verified denuclearization.”
The Security Council has unanimously imposed sanctions on North Korea since 2006, in an attempt to cut funding for Pyongyang’s ballistic and nuclear missile programs.
Pompeo spoke to Ri outside the UN General Assembly and later said he would visit Pyongyang again next month to prepare for a second summit.
Pompeo has already visited North Korea three times this year, but his last trip was not well.
He left Pyongyang in July saying progress had been made, but a few hours later North Korea denounced his “demands as those of a mobster.”
At a meeting with Moon this month, North Korea pledged to dismantle a missile site and a nuclear complex if the United States applied “corresponding measures.”
He said Kim had told him that the “corresponding measures” he was seeking were the security guarantees Trump had promised in Singapore and steps toward normalizing relations with Washington.
Harvard students take a course on how to get enough rest
Thanks to a new course being taught this year at Harvard University, all college students sleep longer in an attempt to fight the growing macho culture of studying all night drinking caffeine.
One professor found that students at the number one university in the world usually have no idea about basic self-care.
Charles Czeisler, professor of sleep medicine at Harvard Medical School, and a specialist at Brigham and Women's Hospital designed the course, believed to be the first of its kind in the U.S.
His motivation to start the course came after giving a talk about how sleep deprivation affects learning.
“At the end of the course, a girl came up and asked me why she just found out about this now, in her senior year.
He said no one had ever told him about the importance of sleep, which surprised me,” he told The Telegraph.
The course, first taught this year, explains to students the basics of how good sleep habits contribute to academic and sporting performance, as well as improving overall well-being.
Paul Barreira, a professor of psychiatry at Harvard Medical School and executive director of the university’s health services, said the university decided to introduce the course after discovering that students were barely asleep during the week.
The one-hour course includes a number of interactive tasks.
In one section, there is a one-bedroom image, where students click on coffee cups, curtains, sneakers and books that inform them of the effects of caffeine and light, as well as the impact of lack of sleep on sports performance and the importance of establishing a sleeping routine.
In another section, participants are informed of how long-term sleep deprivation can increase the risk of heart attack, embolism, depression, and cancer.
Then, a campus icon with interactive icons encourages participants to think about their daily routines.
“We know it’s not going to change the behavior of students instantly.
However, we believe they have a right to know, just as anyone has a right to know the health effects of smoking tobacco,” added Professor Czeisler.
He claimed that the culture of pride in “sailing the night” still exists, adding that modern technology and increasing pressure on students meant that sleep deprivation was a growing problem.
Getting enough sleep and a good quality sleep should be “the secret weapon” for students to combat stress, fatigue and anxiety; even to avoid gaining weight, since sleep deprivation makes the brain feel hungry, which is why they want to eat all the time.
Raymond So, a 19-year-old Californian who studies chemical and physical biology, helped Professor Czeisler design the course after attending one of his classes the previous year during his first year at Harvard.
He pointed out that the course had opened his eyes and inspired him to expand it to the entire campus.
He hopes that the next step will be to ask all graduate students to complete a similar program of study before joining the competitive institution.
Professor Czeisler’s recommendation is for students to think about setting an alarm to go to bed and another to wake up, and to be aware of the harmful effects of the “blue light” emitted by the screens of electrical appliances and LEDs, which can alter circadian rhythms, so they would end up having trouble falling asleep.
