The Global Citizen Festival, which began in 2012, is an extension of the Global Poverty Project, an international awareness group that hopes to end poverty by increasing the number of people actively fighting it.
If you want to receive a free ticket to the event (unless you can afford a VIP ticket), concert attendees have had to complete a number of tasks or “actions,” such as volunteering, sending emails to a world leader, making a phone call, or anything else that serves to raise awareness about your goal of ending poverty.
However, what has Global Citizen achieved 12 years after reaching its goal?
Is the idea of rewarding with a free concert a genuine way of persuading people to take action or is it just a form of so-called “clictivism,” which is called the stance we take when we think we’re doing something really useful when signing an online petition or sending a tweet?
Since 2011, Global Citizen claims to have registered more than 19 million “actions” of its supporters in favor of a large number of diverse goals.
Thanks to these actions, they claim to have gotten world leaders to announce commitments and policies worth more than $37 billion, which will impact on the lives of more than 2.25 billion people by 2030.
At the beginning of 2018, the group cited 390 commitments and announcements that emerged from its shares, of which at least $10 billion have already been paid out or raised.
The group estimates that guaranteed funds have directly affected nearly 649 million people worldwide.
Among the most important commitments is “The Power of Nutrition”, a partnership of UK-based investors and executors united in a common commitment to “help children grow and develop to their full potential.” To this end, they have proposed to provide Rwanda with $35 million to help end the country’s malnutrition after receiving more than 4,700 tweets from Global Cizen contributors.
“Thanks to the support of the UK government, donors, national governments and Global Citizens collaborators like you, we can mark a small milestone in the history of social injustice of malnutrition,” Tracey Ullman, ambassador of “The Power of Nutrition,” told the crowd during a concert in April 2018 in London.
The group also stated that, after having carried out more than 5,000 actions to try to improve nutrition in the UK for mothers and children, the government announced funding for a project, Power of Nutrition, with which 5 million women and children will benefit from nutrition-related interventions.
In response to one of the frequently asked questions on their website about what we believe can be done to remedy extreme poverty,
A Global Citizen contributor responded: “It will be a long and hard road and, on many occasions, we will stumble and fall.
But, as human rights and anti-apartheid movements have already achieved, we will achieve our goals, because we are stronger together.
