Tim Berners-Lee, the inventor of the World Wide Web, is launching a new company that is trying to rival Facebook, Amazon and Google.
Inrupt is the latest project of the technology legend. A company that builds on Berners-Lee’s open source platform Solid.
Solid allows users to choose where to store their data and which people will have access to what information.
In an exclusive interview with Fast Company, Berners-Lee joked that the intention behind Inrupt is “to dominate the world.”
“It has to be now,” he said of the startup.
“This is a historic moment.”
The app uses Solid’s technology so users can create their own “online personal data storage” or POD.
It can contain lists, to-do lists, calendar, music library, and other personal and professional tools.
It’s as if Google Drive, Microsoft Outlook, Slack and Spotify are all available in one browser at the same time.
One thing that is unique about personal online data storage is that it is the user who completely decides who can access what type of information.
The company calls it “personal training through data.”
Inrupt’s idea, according to the company’s CEO, John Bruce, is to incorporate the resources, processes, and skills needed for Solid to reach everyone.
At the moment, the company is made up of Berners-Lee, Bruce, a security platform that IBM bought, some of the included developers who were hired to work on the project, and a community of volunteer programmers.
Starting this week, tech developers around the world could build their own decentralized apps with the tools available on Inrupt’s website.
Berners-Lee said he and his team are not talking to “Facebook and Google about whether or not a radical change is going to be introduced where all of their business models are completely modified overnight.
“We’re not going to ask for permission.”
In a post on Medium on Saturday, Berners-Lee wrote about Inrupt that “its mission is to provide commercial energy and an ecosystem to help protect the integrity and quality of the new website created on Solid.”
In 1994, Berners-Lee transformed the Internet when he founded the World Wide Web Consortium (W3C) at the Massachusetts Institute of Technology.
In recent months, Berners-Lee has played a very influential role in the net neutrality debate.
Despite even launching Inrupt, Berners-Lee will remain the founder and director of the World Wide Web Consortium, the Web Foundation and the Open Data Institute.
“I’m incredibly optimistic about this next era of the web,” Berners-Lee added.
Bernard Vann: the cleric who won a Victory Cross in World War I
The only clergyman in the Church of England who won a Victory Cross during World War I as a fighter has been honored in his hometown 100 years later.
Lt. Col. Rev. Bernard Vann obtained this decoration on September 29, 1918 in the attack of Bellenglise and Lehaucourt.
However, a sniper killed him four days later and never knew he had been awarded the greatest British military honor.
On Saturday, his two grandchildren discovered a memorial stone at a parade in Rushden, Northamptonshire.
One of them, Michael Vann, said it was “of a special symbolism” that the stone was discovered exactly 100 years after the battle that earned him the decoration for his grandfather.
According to the London Gazette, on September 29, 1918, Lieutenant Colonel Vann guided his battalion through the Saint-Quentin Canal "through thick fog and under the intense fire of machine guns and cannons".
He then ran to the line of fire and, with the "greatest courage", advanced the line before reaching a canyon with one hand and knocking down three of the detachment.
Lieutenant Colonel Vann was killed by a German sniper on October 4, 1918, just a month after the war ended.
Michael Vann, 72, said his grandfather’s actions were “so great that I can never reach his height, but they were very enticing.”
He and his brother, Dr. James Vann, also deposited a wreath after the parade, which featured the Brentwood Imperial Youth Band.
Michael Vann said it was "a privilege for him to be part of the parade" and added that "the value of an authentic hero is evident when such a large number of endorsements are shown to him."
MMA fans were up all night for the Bellator 206, but only saw Peppa Pig
Imagine that you stay up all night to see the whole Bellator 206 so that in the end you will not be allowed to see the main event.
The San Jose poster featured 13 fights, six included on the main card, and in the UK it was going to be broadcast live at night on Channel 5.
At 6:00 a.m., just as Gegard Mousasi and Rory MacDonald were preparing to face off, UK viewers were stunned when the show switched to Peppa Pig.
Some were not surprised after having to stay up until early in the morning just to watch the fight.
A Twitter follower described the switch to cartoons as “a heavy joke.”
“There’s government regulation that regulates content that airs after 6 a.m. and this wasn’t appropriate, so they had to switch to children’s programming,” said Dave Schwartz, Bellator’s senior vice president of marketing and communications, when asked about the broadcast.
"Peppa the pig, yes."
Bellator president Scott Coker said they will modify the show to include British viewers in upcoming editions.
“When I think about the rebroadcast option, I think it can work,” Coker said.
"But it's at 6 a.m. on Sunday, so we couldn't do it until Sunday at our own time, which would already be Monday for them.
We're looking at how to do it.
Believe me, when the schedule was changed, a lot of messages were received and not all were kind, precisely.
We tried to fix it, because at first we thought it was a technical problem.
But it wasn’t, it was a government problem.
I can promise that next time it won't happen.
We will reduce it to five fights instead of six, which are the ones we normally did. We tried to offer more than usual so that the fans were happy and we had a good time.
It is a very unfortunate situation.”
Desert Island Discs: Tom Daley felt inferior about his sexuality
Olympic jumper Tom Daley says he grew up feeling inferior to the rest because of his sexuality, although this was, in turn, what motivated him to become a triumphant.
At the age of 24, he told us that he didn’t realize until he got to high school that “not everyone was like me.”
On Radio 4’s first Desert Island Discs show, hosted by Lauren Laverne, he said his intention in talking about gay rights was to convey “hope” to others.
He also told us that becoming a father made him begin to downplay winning the Olympics.
The usual host of this mythical show, Kirsty Young, will be absent for a few months due to illness.
On Laverne’s first show, Daley, who showed himself as a marginalized, said he felt “inferior” to the rest during his childhood, because “it was not socially accepted that you liked boys and girls.”
He said, “To this day, that feeling of inferiority and being different has really given me the power and strength to succeed.”
He wanted to prove that he was “something,” he claimed, so he wasn’t disappointed when he finally discovered his sexuality.
The winner of two bronze medals at the Olympics has become a prominent profile of the LGBT movement and his image has been used at this year’s Commonwealth Games in Australia to demand that more countries decriminalize homosexuality.
He said he told it because he felt fortunate to live in freedom, without retaliation, and wanted to pass on that “hope” to other people.
The three-time world champion declared that it was also a surprise for him to fall in love with a man, the American filmmaker Dustin Lance Black, whom he met in 2013.
Daley married the 20-year-old Oscar winner last year, although he said the age difference had never been an issue.
“When you’ve lived so much since you were so young” (he went to his first Olympics at age 14 and his father died of cancer three years later), it’s hard to find someone the same age who’s gone through the same ups and downs as you.
The couple had a son in June who they called Robert Ray Black-Daley and Daley said his "global outlook" had changed.
“If they had asked me last year, all the answers would have revolved around ‘I have to win a gold medal,’” he said.
“But you know what, there are more important things than Olympic gold medals.
My Olympic gold medal is, without a doubt, Robbie.”
His son is named after his father, Robert, who died in 2011 at the age of 40 after he was diagnosed with brain cancer.
Daley said his father would not accept that he was going to die and, in fact, one of the last things he asked is if they had the passes for London 2012, because he wanted to be in the front row.
“I couldn’t tell him I wasn’t going to be in the front row,” he said.
“I had his hand in my hand when he stopped breathing and it wasn’t until that exact moment when he stopped breathing and died that I realized he wasn’t invincible,” she said.
The following year, Daley competed at the 2012 Olympics and won the bronze medal.
“At that moment I knew that was what I had dreamed of all my life: competing in the pool in front of mine at an Olympics, there was nothing better,” he said.
This fact was also the one that inspired him to choose his first song, Proud by Heather Small, which accompanied him in the preparation phase of the Olympic Games.
Desert Island Discs aired on BBC Radio 4 on Sunday at 11:15 BST.
Mickelson, in low form, stayed on the bench at the Ryder Cup on Saturday
American Phil Mickelson will set a record Sunday when he plays his 47th Ryder Cup game, but will have to reverse his form if he wants to prevent it from becoming a sad milestone.
Mickelson, who was playing at the event every two years to set a record for the 12th time, was knocked out by Captain Furyk for Saturday’s fourballs and foursomes.
Instead of being at the center of the action, as he has done so many times for the United States, the five-time majors champion had to settle for cheering at one point and, at another, trying to perfect his game on the field and be able to rectify what afflicts him.
Never the most direct of drivers, even at the highest moment of his career, the 48-year-old is not in his best shape for the Le Golf National course, where the long rough continually punishes with erroneous blows.
And, if the field is no longer daunting enough, Mickelson, in Sunday’s ninth game, faces brilliant British Open champion Francesco Molinari, who has teamed up with rookie Tommy Fleetwood to win the four games they’ve played this week.
If the Americans, who were four points lower at the start of the 12 individual games, started in an impressive way, Mickelson’s match could have been decisive.
Furyk showed confidence in his partner, he couldn’t say much more either.
“He perfectly understood the role he had today, he slapped me on the back and, surrounding me with his arm, he said he would be ready tomorrow,” Furyk said.
“He has a lot of confidence in himself.
He is in the Hall of Fame and has contributed a lot to these teams before and this week.
I probably couldn’t imagine playing two games.
I thought they would be more, but that’s how it came out and that’s how we thought it had to be.
He wants to be there, like the rest of us.”
On Sunday, Mickelson will surpass Nick Faldo’s mark of most Ryder Cup games played.
It could be the latest in a Ryder Cups trajectory that has never so clearly matched the levels of its individual brand.
Mickelson has 18 wins, 20 losses and 7 equals, although Furyk said his presence brought many more intangible values to the team.
“He’s fun, sarcastic, ingenious, he likes to make fun of others; it’s great to have him on the team,” he explained.
“I think younger players have loved having it as a support, also this week; it was fun.
It brings a lot more than just playing.”
European Captain Thomas Bjorn Knows Leadership May Disappear Very Soon
Thomas Bjorn, the captain of Europe, knows very well that even if you get a substantial lead in the final days of the Ryder Cup, it can easily turn into an uncomfortable tournament.
The Dane made his debut in the 1997 match at Valderrama, where a side led by Seve Ballesteros held a five-point lead over the Americans, but in the end they only managed to knock out the others by a minimal margin, winning 141-2-131-2.
"You don't stop reminding you that we did a great tournament at Valderrama; we did it at Brookline and we lost, we did it at Valderrama and we won, but for very little," Bjorn said, portrayed after watching the 2018 generation win 5-3 on Friday and yesterday leading it with a 10-6 at Le Golf National.
The story will teach me and everyone that this team is not over.
You have to give it all tomorrow.
Go out there and do what you have to do.
This does not end until the points are on the scoreboard.
We have a goal to meet, which is to win this trophy, and that’s all we have to think about.
I say it all the time, I focus on the 12 players of our team, but we are very aware of what is on the other side where they are, no more and no less, than the best players in the world.
Proud of what his players have done on a very tough golf course, Bjorn added: "I wouldn't want to get ahead.
Tomorrow is a different challenge.
What prevails tomorrow is the individual performances and this is different.
It’s great to share what happens with a partner when things go well, but when you’re there alone, you put all your golfing skills to the test.
That’s the message that needs to be conveyed to the players, to get the best out of yourself tomorrow.
Now it’s time to put your partner aside, go and get the best out of yourself.”
In front of Bjorn, his counterpart Jim Furyk will try to get his players to do better individually than they did as couples, with exceptions being Jordan Spieth and Justin Thomas, who scored three points out of four.
Furyk himself has been at both extremes in the last few days of those big tournaments and has been part of the team that won at Brookline and then ended up losing when Europe held the “Mednah Miracle”.
