Thomas is tasked with trying to lead the fight and take on Rory McIlroy in the main game, with Paul Casey, Justin Rose, Jon Rahm, Tommy Fleetwood and Ian Poulter, the other Europeans in the second half of the list.
“I went with this group of guys in this order because I think they cover the whole route,” Bjorn said of their individual teams.
The new German warship, postponed again
The new German Navy frigate should have been commissioned in 2014 to replace the old Cold War-era ships, but it won’t be made until at least next year due to faulty systems and progressively rising costs, local media reported.
The delivery of the "Rheinland-Pfalz", the ship leading the new Baden-Württemberg class frigates, has now been postponed until the first half of 2019, according to a military spokesman.
The ship should have joined the Navy in 2014, but the problems that arose after delivery hampered the completion of the ambitious project.
The four Baden-Wuerttemberg-class ships requested by the Navy in 2007 will replace the old Bremen-class frigates.
We know that they will include a powerful cannon, a set of anti-aircraft and anti-ship missiles, as well as some invisibility technologies, such as very reduced radar, infrared and acoustic signals.
Other important features include longer maintenance periods, so they can be deployed for up to two years away from the ports of origin.
However, continued delays have caused the innovative ships (which were supposed to allow Germany to project its power overseas) to be outdated by the time they begin service, Die Zeit notes.
The unfortunate F125 frigate made headlines last year, when the German Navy officially refused to put the ship into service and returned it to the Blohm & Voss shipyard in Hamburg.
It was the first time the Navy had returned a ship to a shipyard after it was delivered.
Little was known about the reasons behind the return, but German media cited a number of crucial "software and hardware defects" that left the ship virtually useless if sent to a combat mission.
The software deficiencies were particularly important, as the Baden-Wuerttemberg-class ships will be operated by a crew of about 120 sailors – half the staff on the former Bremen-class frigates.
It was also found that the ship is overweight, which reduces its performance and limits the Navy’s ability to add future upgrades.
The 7000-ton "Rheinland-Pfalz" is believed to be twice as heavy as other ships of similar class used by the Germans in World War II.
In addition to the faulty hardware, the price of the entire project, including crew training, has also been a problem.
It is believed to have reached €3.1 billion ($3.6 billion), instead of the initial €2.2 billion.
The problems attributed to the new frigates are of particular relevance in light of the recent warnings about the reduction of Germany’s naval power.
Earlier this year, Hans-Peter Bartels, head of the defense committee of the German parliament, acknowledged that the Navy is "running out of ships capable of deploying".
The officer said the problem has gotten worse over time, because the old boats were dropped but have not been replaced with others.
He regretted that none of the Baden-Wuerttemberg class frigates were able to join the Navy.
National Trust spies on the secret life of bats
This new research, which has been conducted in a state in the Scottish Highlands, attempts to discover how bats use the landscape in their hunt for food.
Everything that is found is expected to shed more light on the behavior of the only flying mammals and help guide upcoming conservation activities.
The study, conducted by the National Trust for Scotland, will follow common bats and sopranos, as well as Daubenton shore bats and long-eared browns from Inverewe Gardens in Wester Ross.
Special recorders will be placed in strategic locations on the property to track bat activities during the season.
NHS staff and volunteers will also conduct mobile investigations with portable detectors.
Experts will analyze the sounds collected in the recordings to discover the frequency of bat calls and what species do it.
A report and a habitat map will then be produced to create a detailed picture of the environment and its behavior.
Rob Dewar, Nature Conservation Advisor for NTS, hopes the results will reveal which areas of the habitat are most important to bats and how each species uses them.
This information will determine the benefits of habitat management work, such as the creation of grasslands and how forests should be maintained for bats and other associated species.
Bat populations in Scotland and the United Kingdom have declined considerably over the past century.
They are under threat from the construction and development that affects their nests and the loss of their habitat.
Wind turbines and electrical wiring can also pose a risk to them, as can insecticidal papers and other chemical treatments of building materials or attacks by domestic cats.
Bats are not really blind,
But because of their night hunting habits, their ears are more useful than their eyes to achieve their goal.
They use a sophisticated echolocation technique that locates ants and obstacles in their flight path.
The NTS, which is responsible for the care of more than 270 historic buildings, 38 important gardens and 76,000 hectares of land across the country, takes bats very seriously.
It has ten trained experts in the field, who are dedicated to conducting regular surveys, nest inspections and, sometimes, rescues.
The organization has even inaugurated Scotland’s first and only bat reserve in the state of Threave in Dumfries and Galloway, which is home to eight of Scotland’s ten bat species.
The property manager, David Thompson, says it’s the ideal territory for them.
“Here at Threave, we have a fantastic bat zone,” he said.
“We have old buildings, lots of veteran trees and all the right habitat.
However, there is still a lot unknown about bats, so the work we do here and in other properties will help us better understand what they need to develop.”
It stresses the importance of checking for bats before carrying out maintenance tasks inside the properties, since a breeding colony can be inadvertently destroyed and 400 females and offspring could be killed, which would mean annihilating an entire local population.
Bats are protected and it is illegal to kill, harass or annoy them, as well as destroy their colonies.
Elisabeth Ferrell, the Scottish officer in charge of the Bat Conservation Trust, has encouraged the public to collaborate.
He said, “We still have a lot to learn about bats and many other species that we don’t know how their populations evolve.”
Ronaldo Denies Rape Allegations as Lawyers Persecute German Magazine
Cristiano Ronaldo has labeled rape allegations as “fake news,” and says people “want to make themselves known” at the expense of their name.
His lawyers have been instructed to denounce the German newspaper Der Spiegel, which is where the statements were published.
