Brexit: Britain would always regret losing automakers
Britain would “repent for life” if it lost its position as a world leader in car manufacturing after Brexit, Industry Secretary Greg Clark said.
He added that it was "worrying" that Toyota UK told the BBC that if Britain left the EU without a deal, it would temporarily halt production at its Burnaston plant near Derby.
“We need a deal,” Mr. Clark said.
The Japanese manufacturer said the impact of customs delays in the event of a no-deal Brexit could lead to job losses.
The Burnaston plant, which makes Toyota’s Auris and Avensis models, produced about 150,000 cars last year, of which 90% were exported to the rest of the European Union.
“My view is that if Britain breaks with the EU at the end of March, there will be production stoppages at our factory,” said Marvin Cooke, Toyota’s general manager in Burnaston.
Other UK automakers have expressed fears about leaving the EU without a deal, especially in relation to cross-border trade, including Honda, BMW and Jaguar Land Rover.
BMW, for example, says it will close its Mini plant in Oxford a month after Brexit.
The main concerns that automakers are referring to revolve around the problems that could arise in the assembly lines in the event of a no-deal Brexit.
Toyota’s production line is based on the “just in time” mode, where parts arrive every 37 minutes from UK and EU suppliers to make custom cars.
If the UK leaves the European Union without a deal on 29 March, there could be a border disruption that the sector says could lead to delays and parts shortages.
It would be impossible for Toyota to house the amount of material equivalent to more than one day of inventory at its Derbyshire plant, the company said, and in that case, production would stop.
Mr Clark said Theresa May’s Chequers plan, where future relations with the EU are established, is “precisely calibrated to avoid such checks at the border crossings.”
“We need a deal. We want to have the best deal that not only allows us to get out of the way right now but we have to take the opportunity,” he said on BBC Radio 4’s Today program.
“Toyota’s evidence, among many other manufacturers, is that we need to be able to continue with what, so far, has been a tremendously successful supply chain set.”
Toyota has not been able to say how long production would stop, but warned that in the long run, added costs would reduce the plant’s competitiveness and ultimately costs.
Peter Tsouvallaris, who has worked at Burnaston for 24 years and is the head of the Unite union at the plant, said its members are increasingly concerned: “In my experience, once those jobs are lost, they never recover.”
A government spokesman said: “We have put in place a precise and convincing plan that delimits our future relations with the EU.”
Trump's meeting with Rosenstein could be postponed again, according to the White House
Donald Trump’s high-risk meeting with Deputy Attorney General Rod Rosenstein could be “postponed another week,” as the dispute over Supreme Court candidate Brett Kavanaugh continues, the White House said on Sunday.
Rosenstein oversees the work of special counsel Robert Mueller, who is investigating interference in the Russian elections, links between Trump’s aid and Russia, and a possible obstruction of justice by the president.
The anticipation of whether Trump decides to fire the deputy attorney general or not and thus compromise Mueller’s independence has fueled Washington’s gossip for months.
Earlier this month, the New York Times reported that Rosenstein recorded his conversations with Trump with a microphone he himself was carrying to try to relegate the president through the 25th Amendment.
Rosenstein denied that it was true.
However, on Monday he went to the White House, amid news reports that he was about to resign.
Instead, a meeting was announced with Trump (who at the time was at the United Nations in New York) for Thursday.
Trump said he would "prefer not" to fire Rosenstein but the meeting had to be postponed to avoid a conflict with the U.S. Senate Judiciary Committee hearing in which Kavanaugh and one of the women who accused him of sexual assault, Dr. Christine Blasey Ford, testified.
On Friday, Trump asked the FBI to investigate the allegations against Kavanaugh for a week, though this would delay the Senate vote.
Trump press secretary Sarah Sanders appeared Sunday on Fox News.
When asked about Rosenstein’s meeting, he said: “No date has been set, it could be this week or another one could be postponed, considering everything that is happening with the Supreme Court.
We will decide on the march and I will inform the press, as I usually do.”
Some reporters would refute that claim: Sanders hasn’t held a press conference at the White House since Sept. 10.
Host Chris Wallace asked what the reasons were.
Sanders said the shortage of press conferences was not due to an aversion to TV journalists acting grandiosely, though he said: "I won't disagree with the fact that they brag."
She then suggested that direct contact between Trump and the press would increase.
“The president does more question-and-answer sessions than any previous president,” he said, while citing without evidence: “We’ve contrasted those numbers.”
The press conferences will continue to be held, Sanders said, but “if the press has the option to ask the president of the United States directly, I think it’s a lot better than doing them to me.
We’ve tried to do it many times and you’ve seen us do it many times in the last few weeks, so this would replace a press conference when you can talk to the president of the United States.”
Trump often answers questions when he leaves the White House or participates in public sessions or press conferences with dignitaries visiting him.
Press conferences with him only happen on very rare occasions.
In fact, this week in New York, the president demonstrated why it was so, where he made a casual and, at times bizarre appearance to the journalists who were congregating there.
Secretary of State for Health writes to NHS Scotland EU workers about their fears of Brexit
The Secretary of State for Health has written to the EU staff working at HHS Scotland to express the country’s gratitude and desire for them to stay with them after Brexit.
Jeane Freeman MSP sent a letter just six months before the UK withdrew from the EU.
The Scottish government has already pledged to cover the cost of citizenship applications for EU members working in public services that are not dependent on central power.
In her letter, Ms Freeman wrote: "During the summer, negotiations between the United Kingdom and the European Union on the exit were followed in which they chose to take the expected decisions this fall.
However, the UK government has also stepped up preparations around a possible scenario in which there would be no agreement.
I know that all of this must be very baffling to you.
