Foreigners will be charged a higher farm transfer tax when they buy property in the UK
Foreigners will be charged a higher farm transfer tax when they buy a property in the UK and the extra money raised with this measure will be used to shelter the “homeless,” according to new Conservative plans.
The change will neutralize the success of the Corbyn offensive to attract younger voters
The farm transfer tax increase will be imposed on those who are not paying taxes in the UK.
The Treasury expects to raise up to 120 million pounds a year to go to the "homeless"
The additional money raised by the tax increase on the transfer of estates to foreign buyers of property in the UK will go to aid for the “homeless,” Theresa May announced today.
The move is meant as an attempt to neutralize the success Jeremy Corbyn is reaping with his promises to provide more affordable housing to attract younger voters and bullying those with higher incomes.
The increase in the farm transfer tax will be levied on individuals and businesses who do not pay taxes in the UK and that money will go to incentivize government policy to combat the problem of begging on the streets.
The surcharge, which is a supplement to the current transmission tax, including also the rise in levels that was introduced two years ago on second-hand homes and the "buy-to-let" system, could be as high as 3%.
The Treasury expects to raise up to 120 million pounds a year with this change.
It is estimated that 13% of London’s new-build properties are purchased by non-UK residents, causing rising prices and making it difficult for first-time buyers to access affordable housing.
Many of the country’s wealthiest areas (especially in the capital) have become “ghost cities” due to the large number of foreign buyers who spend most of their time outside the country.
The new policy comes just weeks after Boris Johnson demanded a reduction in the transmission tax in order to help young people buy their first home.
He accused the large construction companies of maintaining very high prices on properties by eagerly buying land without intending to use it and urged Mrs May to eliminate the quotas that apply to affordable housing to solve the “shameful housing problem” in Britain.
Mr. Corbyn has announced a number of very attractive housing reforms, including rent controls and the end of evictions for no reason.
It also proposes to give local authorities more powers to build new homes.
Mrs May said: “Last year I said that I would dedicate my position as Prime Minister to restoring the British dream of improving the lives of every new generation.
And that means solving the housing market, which is so devastated.
Britain will always be open to those who want to live, work and build a life here.
