U.S.-China trade war could benefit Beijing
The first salvos from the U.S.-China trade war were deafening, and while there is still a long way to go before the battle is over, a rupture between the countries could benefit Beijing, experts say.
Donald Trump, the U.S. president, issued the first warning earlier this year by imposing tariffs on major Chinese exports such as solar panels, steel and aluminum.
The most significant escalation took place this week with new tariffs affecting $200 billion ($150 billion) in products, charging taxes on half of products entering the United States from China.
On all occasions, Beijing has taken equivalent retaliation, recently imposing tariffs of five to ten percent on US products worth $60 billion.
China has pledged to match U.S. attacks, and the world’s second-most powerful economy is unlikely to loosen soon.
Getting Washington to back down would mean yielding to demands, but publicly submitting to the United States would be too embarrassing for Chinese President Xi Jinping.
Still, experts say that if Beijing plays its cards well, pressures from the U.S. trade war could positively help China in the long run by reducing interdependence between the two economies.
“The fact that a quick political decision in Washington or Beijing can set the stage for a plunge in the economy in either country is actually far more dangerous than viewers have acknowledged so far,” said Abigail Grace, Asia-focused associate researcher for the strategic cabinet Center for New American Security.
Syria ready for refugees to return, says foreign minister
Syria says it is ready for the voluntary return of refugees and asks for help to rebuild a country devastated by a war that has been going on for more than seven years.
In a speech before the United Nations General Assembly, Foreign Minister Walid al-Moualem said the country’s conditions were improving.
“The situation on the ground is now more stable and secure thanks to the progress that has been made in the fight against terrorism,” he said.
The government continues to rehabilitate areas destroyed by terrorists to try to restore normality.
All conditions for the voluntary return of refugees who had to leave the country due to terrorism and unilateral economic measures that affected their daily lives and livelihoods are now in place.
The UN estimates that since the war began in 2011, more than 5.5 million Syrians have fled the country.
Another six million people are still living in the country and in need of humanitarian assistance.
Al-Moualem acknowledged that the Syrian regime would appreciate help in rebuilding the devastated country.
But he also stressed that he would not accept conditional aid or aid from the countries that promoted the insurgency.
