Europe regained the crown when the team of Danish captain Thomas Bjorn scored the necessary 14.5 points to beat the United States.
American star Phil Mickelson, who had to fight for most of the tournament, threw his point of departure into the water in the 16 par 3 hole, thus admitting his defeat against Francesco Molinari.
Italian golfer Molinari stood out in all his rounds, becoming one of four players who have never achieved a 5-0-0 since the tournament’s current format began in 1979.
The American Jordan Spieth fell 5-4 to the European team's lowest-ranking player, the Danish Thorbjorn Olesen.
The world’s number one player, Dustin Johnson, fell 2-1 to Englishman Ian Poulter, who could have played his last Ryder Cup.
